WEBVTT

00:00.290 --> 00:02.673
Welcome to Potential Church.

00:02.773 --> 00:05.095
Steph and I are spending some time with my father.

00:05.556 --> 00:07.738
We had a 12-hour surgery.

00:07.818 --> 00:09.180
We appreciate your prayers.

00:09.600 --> 00:11.643
But I just wanted to say thank you.

00:12.123 --> 00:14.686
In just a moment, Pastor Brian's going to be coming out.

00:14.726 --> 00:16.968
He's been here for almost two decades.

00:17.389 --> 00:18.891
He started to get a little bit old.

00:19.271 --> 00:25.618
But he has had an incredible impact in the sense that he served in a lot of different moment ministries along the way.

00:25.730 --> 00:30.116
You're watching me through the technology of a camera.

00:30.156 --> 00:31.478
Well, he started that.

00:31.759 --> 00:34.963
So when he comes out in just a few moments, give him some encouragement.

00:35.284 --> 00:37.507
Ministry can sometimes be lonely.

00:37.627 --> 00:40.151
And I know that it'll make a huge difference.

00:40.391 --> 00:47.181
The other thing I wanted to mention is each baptism, it's so easy to kind of take it for granted.

00:47.401 --> 00:53.330
But we are having the great American baptism party.

00:53.506 --> 00:53.746
Right?

00:53.766 --> 00:55.669
I feel like I ought to be president or something.

00:55.689 --> 00:58.333
The great American baptism party.

00:58.353 --> 00:59.515
It's going to be awesome.

00:59.535 --> 01:00.436
We're going to have fun.

01:00.497 --> 01:01.358
We're going to play games.

01:01.378 --> 01:03.341
We're going to have something to eat.

01:03.361 --> 01:04.102
I hope you'll come.

01:04.643 --> 01:07.607
If you're never stepped into the water, wait.

01:08.529 --> 01:09.110
Be obedient.

01:09.210 --> 01:12.935
Got some incredible things on the other side of your beat.

01:12.955 --> 01:18.965
And if you have, I'm not coming to hang out, you might be encouraged, or maybe even something more special.

01:19.405 --> 01:22.610
God might use you to encourage somebody else.

01:22.882 --> 01:25.047
So it is an amazing summer.

01:25.428 --> 01:32.064
I'm excited to have Pastor Brian and of course his wife, Mindy, and thanks again for being here this weekend.

01:32.364 --> 01:34.770
As we continue our series, subscribe.

02:11.554 --> 02:36.172
Thanks for being here.

02:36.833 --> 02:38.155
Thanks for making this part of your weekend.

02:38.215 --> 02:39.477
I want to welcome all of our campuses.

02:39.557 --> 02:40.338
Glad you're here.

02:40.578 --> 02:41.139
as well.

02:41.179 --> 02:42.120
My name is Brian Vassel.

02:42.140 --> 02:43.701
Thank you, Pastor, for that great introduction.

02:44.402 --> 02:46.224
I'm not old enough to have been here for decades.

02:46.244 --> 02:51.570
I have been here 20, let's see, 21 years now, and I've been on the staff for 19.

02:51.610 --> 02:54.233
And what an incredible blessing it's been every second.

02:54.754 --> 02:55.815
And I want to say thank you again.

02:56.996 --> 02:58.398
Great, great weekend you picked to be here.

02:58.418 --> 03:00.059
We're in a new series called Subscribe.

03:00.079 --> 03:01.401
We kicked it off last week.

03:01.421 --> 03:05.285
Pastor Troy talked about one of our ethos, which is environment, what we value.

03:05.726 --> 03:08.309
And I hope you got a chance to catch that if you didn't, it's on our app.

03:08.329 --> 03:09.650
Now, before I get into today's

03:09.762 --> 03:12.566
talk, I want to make sure that you hear this great news.

03:12.586 --> 03:16.591
They've given me this opportunity to share with you something extraordinarily special.

03:17.192 --> 03:19.856
How many of you have friends or family in Puerto Rico?

03:20.036 --> 03:22.219
Friends or family in Puerto Rico, several of us all of our campuses.

03:23.040 --> 03:33.574
I want to be able to, I want to tell you today, for the very first time this weekend, TroyGramming.com, our TV ministry, will be broadcast for the very first time in Puerto Rico, which is very cool.

03:33.915 --> 03:35.036
They get a chance to connect there.

03:35.077 --> 03:35.677
So that's awesome.

03:36.378 --> 03:39.122
And, and on top of that, even more good news,

03:39.330 --> 03:41.913
We're being broadcast for the very first time in Pensacola.

03:42.013 --> 03:43.515
So two new places.

03:43.655 --> 03:51.604
Yeah, Grandpa Plaza, all of our friends in Pensacola, you guys get a chance to share the church with your friends and invite them to one of our campuses.

03:51.644 --> 03:52.765
Man, we're excited about this.

03:53.326 --> 03:56.730
I want to say before we go any further, just a genuine heartfelt thank you.

03:58.031 --> 03:58.432
Thank you.

03:58.612 --> 03:59.753
Your generosity.

04:00.314 --> 04:04.178
All of our Temple Centurions who gave above and beyond their ties and offerings.

04:04.546 --> 04:11.713
You make this possible, and I really believe with my whole heart that one day we'll be sitting at that cracker barrel in heaven, but there's gotta be a cracker barrel in heaven, right?

04:12.073 --> 04:29.611
We're on the porch of the cracker barrel in heaven, and somebody's gonna walk up to you and say, thank you, you don't know who I am, but because of your generosity, because you reached beyond your comfort levels and giving, and you say, I wanna put TV in places where it's not, and bring the church to where it's not, that they're in heaven because of your generosity.

04:30.412 --> 04:31.913
And to me, that's amazing.

04:31.933 --> 04:32.914
What more could you give

04:33.058 --> 04:34.841
Your time too, your treasure too.

04:34.901 --> 04:37.746
It's such an awesome opportunity God's given us to reach the world.

04:37.767 --> 04:38.187
So thank you.

04:38.748 --> 04:40.912
We're in a series called Subscribe.

04:40.932 --> 04:42.695
I hope you subscribe to Pastor Troy's vlog.

04:42.796 --> 04:43.677
It is awesome.

04:43.697 --> 04:45.961
It's awesome to be able to hear from his heart.

04:45.981 --> 04:47.664
He shares all kinds of stuff.

04:47.685 --> 04:55.398
If you think of Pastor goes home and prays and studies and floats above the ground or glows or whatever you think of Pastor does in their own time, watch his vlog.

04:55.419 --> 04:57.362
I promise you, after one of them, you'll realize

04:57.602 --> 05:00.946
that we're just normal everyday people that do some really cool stuff.

05:00.966 --> 05:02.288
So I wanna give you the opportunity.

05:02.348 --> 05:06.793
Make sure you go on YouTube and check it out, subscribe to that, to that vlog.

05:07.194 --> 05:11.079
We're telling you, we're talking about ethos number two, something we hope that you can subscribe to.

05:11.319 --> 05:13.361
Ethos are our values here at Potential Church.

05:13.642 --> 05:17.446
And today we're gonna talk about something near and dear to my heart, diversity.

05:18.267 --> 05:20.730
One of our values here at Potential Church is diversity.

05:20.770 --> 05:22.152
Now, I wanna read you the definition.

05:22.172 --> 05:23.454
This is right off of our website.

05:23.914 --> 05:26.898
Here's how Potential Church defines diversity.

05:27.074 --> 05:37.428
Having people who are different races, different cultures, different ages, speak different languages, different life stages, different sexes empowered and represented in every context.

05:37.729 --> 05:40.753
This is our heartbeat as a church.

05:40.773 --> 05:43.036
It's not just something we say, we want to be a diverse church.

05:43.076 --> 05:44.918
We want to have people from all over the place.

05:44.938 --> 05:51.728
We really mean this, from the people we put on our video screens in the stage, to people in the lobby, to people on our teams that are hired as part of the staff.

05:52.789 --> 05:55.212
Diversity is part of our DNA.

05:55.533 --> 05:56.434
It's woven in.

05:56.962 --> 05:58.464
It's not something we give lip service to.

05:58.484 --> 06:01.609
We really truly want to have a diverse church.

06:02.210 --> 06:03.772
But there's another definition for diversity.

06:03.792 --> 06:04.693
It's there in your outline.

06:05.394 --> 06:06.496
All of you guys online as well.

06:06.516 --> 06:09.741
There's a little note part there you can read along with us on our app as well.

06:10.081 --> 06:13.526
This is the condition of having or being composed of differing elements.

06:13.546 --> 06:14.648
This is right out of the dictionary.

06:15.449 --> 06:17.292
Variety, circle that word variety if you would.

06:18.494 --> 06:20.697
The inclusion of different types of people.

06:21.138 --> 06:22.119
Circle the word inclusion.

06:23.040 --> 06:24.082
That's an important word.

06:25.090 --> 06:31.537
The inclusion of different types of people such as people of different races or cultures in a group or organization, a lot of big words there.

06:31.958 --> 06:36.243
A lot of important ones like inclusion, variety, different people.

06:37.784 --> 06:43.391
We're going to talk about a lot of those words today and how they can help us appreciate and subscribe to diversity.

06:43.691 --> 06:48.596
You know, I did a lot of research about diversity and I kept coming up with the same word time and time again.

06:48.637 --> 06:49.858
The word was tolerance.

06:50.879 --> 06:51.780
I'd read these websites.

06:51.860 --> 06:53.522
We are racially tolerant.

06:54.050 --> 06:55.612
We are gender tolerant.

06:55.632 --> 06:56.974
We are ethnically tolerant.

06:56.994 --> 06:58.316
I thought tolerance.

06:58.356 --> 06:59.839
Now, that's an interesting word.

07:00.780 --> 07:04.826
Because when I think of the word tolerance, I think I'm tolerant of the weather in South Florida.

07:05.447 --> 07:07.069
It's hot down here, isn't it?

07:07.089 --> 07:08.832
Now, you guys are friends in Peru, it's the winter.

07:09.653 --> 07:11.676
So I've asked to be transferred for the summer there.

07:12.237 --> 07:13.178
Enjoy the winter and come back.

07:13.198 --> 07:20.289
But anyway, I'm tolerant of my wife asking me to put the seat back down in the bathroom when I'm done.

07:21.611 --> 07:23.634
But tolerance is such a weak word, isn't it?

07:23.842 --> 07:25.645
I'm tolerant of other races.

07:26.586 --> 07:28.088
I'm tolerant of other genders.

07:28.128 --> 07:30.291
I'm tolerant of the people of different age groups.

07:30.352 --> 07:32.194
Tolerance is way too weak of a word.

07:33.576 --> 07:35.419
I put this in your nose, if you would, please fill it in.

07:36.601 --> 07:38.584
Diversity isn't meant to be tolerated.

07:38.624 --> 07:40.066
It's meant that you be celebrated.

07:40.086 --> 07:45.594
The differences between you and I aren't supposed to be put up with, celebrate it.

07:47.196 --> 07:49.720
God made us all unique and different.

07:49.820 --> 07:53.746
And I love that, not to be put up with, but to celebrate.

07:55.362 --> 08:04.891
other cultures, other people at other parts of their lives, different life stages, maybe people that are older, people that are younger, not tolerate them, but celebrate them.

08:04.911 --> 08:06.853
I wrote this in my notes, tolerance isn't enough.

08:07.594 --> 08:11.418
Christ wants us to celebrate those differences and come together to change the world.

08:12.839 --> 08:17.484
Not tolerance, celebration, people that are different.

08:17.504 --> 08:18.285
You know what else I discovered?

08:18.505 --> 08:19.566
But let's do a little experiment.

08:19.586 --> 08:20.166
I love doing this.

08:20.467 --> 08:23.730
On your notes, all of our campuses, there's a little scale, one to 10.

08:24.162 --> 08:27.228
Do me a favor, circle the number that you think best represents you.

08:27.709 --> 08:30.574
One means you're totally normal, okay?

08:30.855 --> 08:36.044
You are the vanilla ice cream of the group, the plain Jane normal, you are normal.

08:36.085 --> 08:38.329
Everybody go ahead and do this, I'm not gonna look at it, I promise.

08:39.150 --> 08:43.218
One means you're totally normal, 10, oh 10s.

08:43.778 --> 08:49.365
You are the Mickey Mouse hat in public like me wearing people that don't care what anybody thinks.

08:49.385 --> 08:51.107
You're just way on the outside fringe.

08:51.127 --> 08:53.550
So one means you're normal, 10 means you're different.

08:53.590 --> 08:54.832
Circle one of those if you would.

08:55.592 --> 08:56.594
Just pick which one you are.

08:56.634 --> 08:58.116
Again, and maybe you're in between somewhere.

08:58.576 --> 09:01.880
One is totally normal, 10 is interesting.

09:03.122 --> 09:03.702
Which one are you?

09:03.883 --> 09:08.268
Now I would guess without looking at your answers, most of you probably circled a three, a four, or a five.

09:09.750 --> 09:11.492
Because that's what the research showed me this week.

09:11.772 --> 09:13.234
Most people don't think they're normal.

09:13.858 --> 09:15.300
Or excuse me, most people don't think they're different.

09:15.401 --> 09:17.784
Everybody thinks they're kind of normal, right?

09:17.804 --> 09:18.305
You're all normal.

09:18.325 --> 09:20.128
This whole section right here, you guys are all normal.

09:20.689 --> 09:22.192
Pensacola, you guys are normal.

09:23.053 --> 09:24.575
We're just don't want to admit they were different.

09:24.595 --> 09:30.725
But you know, I want to prove to you, everybody here today, all of our campuses, everybody is not normal.

09:32.909 --> 09:33.470
You're different.

09:34.592 --> 09:35.493
Look down your rows.

09:36.795 --> 09:37.316
Good grief.

09:37.356 --> 09:38.478
Look at the people around you.

09:39.640 --> 09:40.882
They're different than you are, aren't they?

09:42.050 --> 09:43.672
And now we're only going by appearance, right?

09:43.692 --> 09:45.694
They look differently than we do.

09:46.035 --> 09:47.196
The fact is, please fill this in.

09:47.536 --> 09:52.382
All of us in this room, all of us at all of our campuses and online, all of us are different to somebody.

09:52.442 --> 09:52.963
Did you know that?

09:53.904 --> 09:56.026
Somebody wouldn't wear the clothes you wore today.

09:56.767 --> 09:59.410
In fact, they wouldn't be caught dead in them, right?

09:59.430 --> 10:00.972
Some people like asparagus.

10:02.514 --> 10:04.296
Some people think it tastes like wet socks.

10:05.998 --> 10:08.180
Some people have a lot of money.

10:08.941 --> 10:09.522
Some don't.

10:10.530 --> 10:16.436
Some people parent well, and some people look at the way their parents can go, I would never parent my child like that.

10:17.317 --> 10:21.962
Everybody in the room, everybody in the sound of my voice is different to somebody else.

10:23.804 --> 10:25.706
So is there even a normal?

10:26.207 --> 10:26.627
I don't know.

10:27.728 --> 10:29.090
Everybody in the room today is different.

10:29.430 --> 10:31.933
In fact, give me a favor, turn to your neighbor and tell them you are different.

10:31.973 --> 10:32.293
Go ahead.

10:36.938 --> 10:38.019
Some of you guys got a little aggressive.

10:38.039 --> 10:40.402
You are so different.

10:42.306 --> 10:44.490
And by the way, not turn to the same neighbor and say, but that's okay.

10:45.531 --> 10:46.132
That's okay.

10:46.693 --> 10:47.595
Validate them, right?

10:47.615 --> 10:48.616
They're going to lose sleep over that.

10:48.637 --> 10:49.157
It's okay.

10:49.798 --> 10:50.460
You're different.

10:50.820 --> 10:51.601
It's okay.

10:52.202 --> 10:54.647
That's why there's 31 flavors at the ice cream parlor.

10:55.688 --> 10:57.772
If everybody were rum raisin, life would be boring, right?

10:58.192 --> 11:02.520
Everybody's different.

11:02.540 --> 11:03.281
Everybody's different.

11:03.662 --> 11:06.386
I didn't realize this until my very first year in school.

11:07.234 --> 11:13.283
Remember when you're in school, you get a new teacher, you get new school supplies, new folders, and you know when I found out I was different?

11:13.924 --> 11:15.006
My favorite period of the day.

11:20.054 --> 11:20.294
Lunch.

11:22.417 --> 11:29.608
And I grabbed my land of the lost lunchbox, and I sat at a very small table like this one, and I looked around.

11:30.590 --> 11:35.858
And I went to unpack my lunchbox and eat my sandwich, which was peanut butter and banana, that's what I liked.

11:36.226 --> 11:39.489
Took out my snack pack and my nutty bar and everything else my mom had packed for me.

11:39.809 --> 11:41.171
And you know what I realized about lunch?

11:42.472 --> 11:43.493
Not everybody eats what I eat.

11:44.854 --> 11:47.497
And then looked around the table and I realized not everybody looks how I look.

11:47.517 --> 11:51.761
And my parents had told me, don't worry Brian, it's gonna be okay when you get to school, they're all gonna be just like you.

11:54.484 --> 11:56.646
They're not.

11:56.666 --> 12:03.272
There were people, there were kids in that room that had darker skin than me, kids that had lighter skin than me, kids that spoke languages I didn't even understand.

12:03.773 --> 12:05.074
Kids that ate like,

12:05.186 --> 12:07.708
But hot food for lunch, I ate cold sandwiches.

12:13.654 --> 12:14.275
But I'm through that.

12:17.258 --> 12:22.803
Redheads, troublemakers, jocks, non-jocks, geeks, you name it, they were in the lunchroom, and I'd never seen them before.

12:22.923 --> 12:26.446
Boy, my whole world expanded.

12:27.808 --> 12:34.354
I realized for the first time that I was different, and they were different too, and that I was part of a much, much bigger world

12:34.882 --> 12:36.023
than I'd ever been in before.

12:36.083 --> 12:38.906
And I had a choice to make that day.

12:40.447 --> 12:47.014
Reject those that are different, or get to know them, and get involved in their lives.

12:48.635 --> 12:50.257
Boy, I'm so glad I chose that second one.

12:51.278 --> 12:52.018
I chose that day.

12:52.078 --> 12:53.540
If they're different than I am, it's cool.

12:54.060 --> 12:55.081
Let's be friends anyway.

12:55.121 --> 12:56.102
Let's get to know each other.

12:56.483 --> 12:59.585
And that decision, way back then, changed my life.

13:01.127 --> 13:02.268
That's what we're gonna talk about today.

13:02.388 --> 13:04.370
How do we deal with people that are different than we are?

13:05.506 --> 13:06.547
How do we get along with them?

13:06.608 --> 13:10.413
Not just get along, not just tolerate difference, but celebrate it.

13:11.474 --> 13:16.681
Maybe today some of us in this room or one of our campuses, maybe you've just been tolerating those that are different.

13:16.701 --> 13:17.683
Maybe you've been avoiding them.

13:19.645 --> 13:22.109
People that are different frighten you for some reason or another.

13:23.030 --> 13:28.197
I don't know what it is, but today we're gonna talk about how to celebrate and get along with those that are different than we are.

13:28.237 --> 13:31.081
So I'm gonna invite you to fill this in all of our campuses, number one.

13:31.321 --> 13:32.082
Here's how to do that.

13:32.142 --> 13:34.866
Number one, don't sit at the same table every day.

13:36.226 --> 13:38.309
Don't sit at the same table every day in the lunchroom.

13:38.469 --> 13:41.452
You know, it would have been much easier if I could have just sat at the same table.

13:41.492 --> 13:43.275
Now, we could sit wherever we wanted in lunch.

13:43.755 --> 13:46.939
But every day, I come to the same place with my same friends every day.

13:47.380 --> 13:49.422
And we could just sit around and talk about Star Wars.

13:49.462 --> 13:50.463
That's what we were all into.

13:50.784 --> 13:56.050
Like, what was the number of the docking bay when Obi-Wan was trying to hire Han and Chewie?

13:56.330 --> 13:58.293
And he was in the cantina.

13:58.473 --> 14:00.395
And he said, meet me in docking bay number what?

14:01.497 --> 14:01.797
Anybody?

14:03.099 --> 14:04.000
It's just like school again.

14:04.040 --> 14:05.101
Nobody else understands me.

14:05.121 --> 14:05.842
It's fine.

14:09.026 --> 14:15.034
Oh, by myself, it's 94, but you should know that.

14:15.054 --> 14:19.621
Now, somebody over here knew it, and you were just not saying it.

14:20.342 --> 14:21.583
You put me out in a weird spot.

14:22.965 --> 14:25.308
But I could have sat around the same people and talked about the same things.

14:25.368 --> 14:25.549
Why?

14:25.569 --> 14:26.730
Because I was comfortable around them.

14:26.770 --> 14:27.371
They got me.

14:27.952 --> 14:28.833
They understood me.

14:30.756 --> 14:32.278
But what a boring lunch that would have become.

14:34.281 --> 14:38.226
Some of us live very boring, one note lives.

14:38.818 --> 14:43.685
because we just don't want to pick up our lunches and sit at a different table for once.

14:43.705 --> 14:44.827
Man, I'm so glad I did that.

14:45.968 --> 14:47.270
You know what I would have missed out on?

14:47.290 --> 14:51.897
I would have missed out on everything if I hadn't picked different tables to sit at.

14:52.418 --> 14:54.240
We've got to choose to sit at different tables.

14:55.022 --> 15:01.110
I needed to hear about different viewpoints and different cultures, different ways of problem solving, different ways of thinking.

15:02.693 --> 15:03.354
That was important.

15:03.474 --> 15:05.176
You know what I heard at the nerdy table?

15:05.577 --> 15:06.418
Nerdy things.

15:08.610 --> 15:09.992
Well, I'm so glad I picked a different table.

15:10.173 --> 15:13.678
I mean, I love my friends and all, but I got to make new friends that were different.

15:13.698 --> 15:16.463
And they expanded my palate, my horizon, my open my eyes.

15:16.563 --> 15:19.107
Wow, the world works differently than I thought.

15:19.848 --> 15:20.950
God had this in mind too.

15:21.271 --> 15:23.474
I put a verse there in your outline, Genesis chapter 11.

15:23.514 --> 15:27.260
Now what's happened here after the flood, God's people have decided to build a tower.

15:27.841 --> 15:30.145
And they want to build a tower so tall, it can almost reach God.

15:30.165 --> 15:31.467
They called it the tower of Babel.

15:32.228 --> 15:35.634
And God says, okay, well, that's not a good idea.

15:36.642 --> 15:37.864
Because they were so proud of themselves.

15:37.884 --> 15:39.566
They said, we all speak the same language, God.

15:40.007 --> 15:41.308
We all have the same customs, God.

15:41.328 --> 15:41.629
Look at us.

15:41.649 --> 15:42.510
We're all the same.

15:42.690 --> 15:44.172
We're all sitting at the same table, God.

15:44.192 --> 15:44.773
Isn't that good?

15:44.993 --> 15:47.016
And God says, no, well, let's see what God said.

15:47.977 --> 15:53.104
God said in Genesis 11, come, let's go down and confuse the people with what?

15:53.985 --> 15:54.866
Different languages.

15:54.987 --> 15:55.788
Let's mix it up here.

15:56.008 --> 15:57.790
Then they won't be able to understand each other.

15:57.951 --> 15:58.191
What?

15:59.092 --> 16:00.354
In that way, the Lord, what?

